/F2 14.00 Tf 54.00 738.00 Td (18. What is Reciprocal Rank Fusion?) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 714.10 Td (Reciprocal Rank Fusion, or RRF, combines multiple ranked lists without needing to compare their) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 700.60 Td (raw scores directly.) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 681.10 Td (This matters because keyword scores and vector distances are not naturally comparable. A) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 667.60 Td (ts_rank_cd score and a cosine distance have different meanings and scales.) Tj
/F4 8.50 Tf 68.00 644.10 Td (hybrid_score = semantic_weight / \(rrf_k + semantic_rank\)) Tj
/F4 8.50 Tf 68.00 633.10 Td (             + keyword_weight  / \(rrf_k + keyword_rank\)) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 616.10 Td (If a chunk ranks well in both semantic and keyword search, both sides contribute to its final) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 602.60 Td (score.) Tj
/F2 14.00 Tf 54.00 575.10 Td (19. What is rrf_k?) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 551.20 Td (rrf_k is a tuning constant used in the RRF formula. In this project, the backend passes 50.) Tj
/F4 8.50 Tf 68.00 527.70 Td (semantic_weight / \(50 + semantic_rank\)) Tj
/F4 8.50 Tf 68.00 516.70 Td (+ keyword_weight / \(50 + keyword_rank\)) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 499.70 Td (Adding rrf_k prevents rank 1 from overpowering everything else. A smaller rrf_k makes top ranks) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 486.20 Td (more dominant. A larger rrf_k makes rank differences less dramatic.) Tj
/F4 8.50 Tf 68.00 462.70 Td (With rrf_k = 50:) Tj
/F4 8.50 Tf 68.00 451.70 Td (rank 1  -> 1 / 51 = 0.0196) Tj
/F4 8.50 Tf 68.00 440.70 Td (rank 5  -> 1 / 55 = 0.0182) Tj
/F4 8.50 Tf 68.00 429.70 Td (rank 20 -> 1 / 70 = 0.0143) Tj
/F2 14.00 Tf 54.00 404.70 Td (20. Why not use rrf_k in keyword-only or semantic-only mode?) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 380.80 Td (Because RRF is useful when fusing multiple ranked lists. Keyword-only mode has one list.) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 367.30 Td (Semantic-only mode has one list.) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 347.80 Td (With only one list, RRF would preserve the same ordering and only change the score shape. It) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 334.30 Td (would not add new retrieval value.) Tj
/F4 8.50 Tf 68.00 310.80 Td (Keyword mode  -> use ts_rank_cd directly) Tj
/F4 8.50 Tf 68.00 299.80 Td (Semantic mode -> use vector distance directly) Tj
/F4 8.50 Tf 68.00 288.80 Td (Hybrid mode   -> use RRF because two ranking systems must be merged) Tj
/F2 14.00 Tf 54.00 263.80 Td (21. What is HNSW?) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 239.90 Td (HNSW means Hierarchical Navigable Small World. It is an approximate nearest-neighbor index for) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 226.40 Td (vector search.) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 206.90 Td (HNSW builds a graph where nearby vectors are connected. During search, it walks through the) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 193.40 Td (graph toward closer and closer vectors instead of comparing the query vector against every) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 179.90 Td (stored vector.) Tj
/F1 9.50 Tf 66.00 160.40 Td (- Good query performance.) Tj
/F1 9.50 Tf 66.00 144.58 Td (- High recall for approximate vector search.) Tj
/F1 9.50 Tf 66.00 128.75 Td (- No separate training step.) Tj
/F1 9.50 Tf 66.00 112.93 Td (- Works well as new vectors are inserted.) Tj
/F1 9.50 Tf 66.00 97.10 Td (- Usually a strong default for RAG apps.) Tj
/F1 10.00 Tf 54.00 81.28 Td (Tradeoff: HNSW can use more memory and can take longer to build than simpler vector index types.) Tj
/F1 8 Tf 286.00 28 Td (5) Tj
